What is the remainder when $2001 \cdot 2002 \cdot 2003 \cdot 2004 \cdot 2005$ is divided by 19?
inference:
The remainder when $n$ is divided by 19 is the same as the remainder when $(n \mod 19)$ is divided by 19. 
So, we can write
$$2001 \cdot 2002 \cdot 2003 \cdot 2004 \cdot 2005 \equiv (2001 \mod 19) \cdot (2002 \mod 19) \cdot (2003 \mod 19) \cdot (2004 \mod 19) \cdot (2005 \mod 19) \pmod{19}.$$

Now, we calculate each of the remainders:
$$2001 \equiv 1 \pmod{19},$$

$$2002 \equiv 2 \pmod{19},$$

$$2003 \equiv 3 \pmod{19},$$

$$2004 \equiv 4 \pmod{19},$$

$$2005 \equiv 5 \pmod{19}.$$

So, we have
$$2001 \cdot 2002 \cdot 2003 \cdot 2004 \cdot 2005 \equiv 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \cdot 5 \equiv 120 \equiv \boxed{1} \pmod{19}.$$

Final Answer: $\boxed{1}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: Reducing each factor modulo 19 first, we see that $2001 \cdot 2002 \cdot 2003 \cdot 2004 \cdot 2005 \equiv 6 \cdot 7 \cdot 8 \cdot 9 \cdot 10 \equiv 30240 \equiv \boxed{11} \pmod{19}$.
